  Memory Management
  - process of allocation and de-allocation of objects
    - Java has automatic memory management system which is divided inti two parts
        -> JVM Memory Structure & Garbage collection

Memory: space that stores values, instructions, or data.

Memory Structure:
2 Memory types:
 - stack: Methods, local variables (variables within a method body)
 - Heap: Instances (Objects), Instances Variables(primitive or reference)
                    ^
                    |
          whenever "new" keyword is used

STACK:
- holds local variables until method lasts -> once execution of method is completed it will be cleared from stack
- last-in-first-out process -> created first main then another method, last method to be creates will be cleared first
- grows / shrinks as any new method is called and terminated
- has auto-allocation an de-allocation feature -> no need to do anything for method or local variable to be cleared
- full memory -> stackoverflowerror
- faster in access when compared to Heap

HEAP:
- comes in everytime when object is created -> "new" keyword creates new memory will be opened and dedicated to that object
- uses "garbage collector" to remove objects tha have no reference -> eventually object will be cleared to make space
- when full -> outofmemoryerror
- slower that stack -> heap processes objects slower than stack does methods and local variables

